{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d80b6e40-f8eb-47f0-978c-caacdd116057","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on the `MauiAppBuilder` to map platform callbacks to cross-platform hooks.\n\nIn your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android Activity.OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android Activity.OnStop\n        }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Platform directives (`#if ANDROID`, `#elif IOS`) ensure each block only compiles for its target.\n- **`OnPause`** (Android) ≈ app partially obscured; **`OnStop`** ≈ fully hidden. **`DidEnterBackground`** is the iOS equivalent of `OnStop`.\n- You can also subscribe to the cross-platform `Window.Deactivated` event for a single handler, but it's less granular than the per-platform hooks shown above.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"18f03a27-1dea-42ce-b737-9227ac9b14cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"D442:21BACA:1BE1D83:1F758B6:6A07C168"},"id":"11edd6c3-ca89-4368-ac5f-a753b8fb86e4","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:59:29.410Z","parentId":"965f600f-aba7-48fb-b68e-88d6962fd301"}
